L. (
<bibRefCitation author="Spencer, K. A. &amp; Steyskal, G. C." box="[159,448,907,934]" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" pagination="1 - 478" refId="ref42797" refString="Spencer, K. A. &amp; Steyskal, G. C. (1986) Manual of the Agromyzidae (Diptera) of the United States. USDA Agricultural Research Service Agriculture Handbook, 638, 1 - 478. https: // doi. org / 10.5962 / bhl. title. 119606" type="journal article" year="1986">Spencer &amp; Steyskal 1986</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="15.[151,1436,799,1258]" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,354,943,969]" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">Larval mine.</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[370,506,943,970]" captionStart="FIGURES 59–72" captionStartId="48.[151,264,1756,1780]" captionTargetBox="[171,1416,181,1732]" captionTargetId="figure-27@48.[171,1416,181,1732]" captionTargetPageId="48" captionText="FIGURES 59–72. Mines and other feeding damage of Agromyzinae on host plants: 59: Agromyza aristata Malloch on Celtis laevigata; 60: Melanagromyza arnoglossi Eiseman &amp; Lonsdale, spec. nov. on Arnoglossum sp.; 61: M. hieracii Eiseman &amp; Lonsdale, spec. nov. on Hieracium scabrum; 62: M. minimoides Spencer on Rudbeckia lacinata; 63: same, section of flower head with puparia inside; 64: Ophiomyia abutilivora Spencer on Abutilon theophrasti; 65: same; 66: Melanagromyza verbenivora Eiseman &amp; Lonsdale, spec. nov. on Verbena stricta, spiral gallery in stem with resulting leaf wilting; 67: same, affected seedhead; 68: Ophiomyia carolinensis Spencer on Symphyotrichum patens; 69: O. cf. frosti Spencer on Lactuca (puparium at upper right); 70: O. rugula Eiseman &amp; Lonsdale, spec. nov. on Baccharis halimifolia; 71: same; 72: same, backlit, showing empty puparium." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4545357" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4545357/files/figure.png" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">Figs. 64–65</figureCitation>
) The larva mines up and down the stem, forming an irregular, gall-like “welt” and associated scarring.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="15.[151,1436,799,1258]" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,328,1015,1041]" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">Puparium.</emphasis>
Whitish to yellowish; formed within the stem, with the anterior spiracles projecting through the epidermis.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="15.[151,1436,799,1258]" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,505,1087,1113]" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">Phenology and voltinism.</emphasis>
<materialsCitation ID-GBIF-Occurrence="3069844456" county="October" location="September" municipality="August" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" specimenCount="1" stateProvince="Mississippi">
The only reared specimens in the 
<typeStatus box="[904,952,1088,1114]" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">type</typeStatus>
series are from 
<collectingRegion box="[1140,1268,1087,1113]" country="United States of America" name="Mississippi" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">Mississippi</collectingRegion>
with a date of 22 
<collectingCounty box="[187,281,1123,1149]" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">October</collectingCounty>
; whether this was the collection or emergence date was not stated, but either way they would seem to represent a different generation from our 
<collectingRegion box="[607,663,1160,1186]" country="United States of America" name="Iowa" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">Iowa</collectingRegion>
specimens, which emerged from green stems in late July. Adults have been collected in 
<collectingMunicipality box="[346,427,1195,1221]" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">August</collectingMunicipality>
and 
<location LSID="urn:lsid:plazi:treatment:0395A00B702DEB432A99FD6F616763D4:8EE347C6702DEB432BECFB77670B63FB" box="[482,602,1195,1221]" county="October" municipality="August" name="September" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" stateProvince="Mississippi">September</location>
in 
<collectingRegion box="[637,758,1195,1221]" country="United States of America" name="Minnesota" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">Minnesota</collectingRegion>
, and in 
<location LSID="urn:lsid:plazi:treatment:0395A00B702DEB432A99FD6F616763D4:8EE347C6702DEB432940FB7766C663FB" box="[846,919,1195,1221]" county="October" municipality="August" name="March" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" stateProvince="Mississippi">March</location>
in 
<collectingRegion box="[954,1035,1195,1221]" country="United States of America" name="Florida" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">Florida</collectingRegion>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Spencer, K. A. &amp; Steyskal, G. C." box="[1050,1340,1195,1222]" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" pagination="1 - 478" refId="ref42797" refString="Spencer, K. A. &amp; Steyskal, G. C. (1986) Manual of the Agromyzidae (Diptera) of the United States. USDA Agricultural Research Service Agriculture Handbook, 638, 1 - 478. https: // doi. org / 10.5962 / bhl. title. 119606" type="journal article" year="1986">Spencer &amp; Steyskal 1986</bibRefCitation>
)
</materialsCitation>
.
</paragraph>
